FIG. 1 shows a telecommunications environment including a data analysis system;


FIG. 2 details the data analysis system identified in FIG. 1 having a plurality of large disc storage devices arranged to store data tables;


FIGS. 3A3B, 4A and 4B illustrate examples of data tables, of the type stored on data storage devices shown in FIG. 2.


FIGS. 5 and 6 illustrate examples of indexes derived from the data contained within the table shown in FIG. 3A;


FIG. 7 illustrates a database structure implemented within the environment shown in FIG. 2, including a process for specifying indexes;


FIG. 8 illustrates processes performed within the environment shown in FIG. 7, including a process for a specifying index sets;


FIG. 9 illustrates the process for specifying index sets identified in FIG. 8, including a process for modelling a live database, a process for analzsing typical SQL statements, a process for base cost calculation, a process for identifying potential indexes and a process for specifying preferred indexes;


FIG. 10 details the process for modelling the live database, identified in FIG. 9;


FIG. 11 details the process for analysing SQL statements identified in FIG. 9;


FIG. 12 illustrates a table of data created using the process identified in FIG. 11;


FIG. 13 details the process for calculating a base cost, identified in FIG. 9;


FIG. 14 details the process for identifying and ordering potential indexes illustrated in FIG. 9;


FIG. 15 details the process for specifying a preferred set of indexes, identified in FIG. 9;


FIG. 16 details an example of data produced during the process illustrated in FIG. 15;


FIG. 17 illustrates the generation of new combination indexes using the process detailed in FIG. 15; and


FIG. 18 illustrates a procedure for establishing indexes within a live database.
